  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Contreras Homer Powers Boston Past New York Yankees",
    "subheadline": "Boston Red Sox beats New York Yankees.",
    "lead_angle": "Willson Contreras sent a Will Warren fastball deep into the Fenway night, a two-run shot that established a lead the Boston Red Sox would not surrender. The blast was part of a relentless early attack that buried the New York Yankees in a 6-1 defeat Friday. Boston starter Payton Tolle baffled the Yankee bats all evening, cruising to a victory against his counterpart Warren, who was knocked out of the game after just three innings of work. The Red Sox simply out-hit and out-pitched their rivals from the first frame forward.\n\nBoston broke the game open in the second inning. With runners in scoring position against a reeling Warren, catcher Connor Wong delivered a sharp single back through the box to plate two more. That pushed the lead to three and took the air out of the visiting dugout. The Yankees never mounted a serious threat from that point on, struggling to string together hits or solve Tolle’s mix of pitches. Wong's single was all the breathing room the Red Sox would need.\n\nContreras was the clear engine for the Boston offense. The veteran backstop finished the night 2-for-3 with the homer and two runs batted in, providing the power from the cleanup spot. For a Red Sox team clawing for position in a tight divisional race, beating the Yankees so soundly at home sends a clear message. This win tightens the standings and gives Boston a critical head-to-head victory as the season marches on.",
    "reason": "Best game on today's slate."
  },
